.SH NAME
Range.surroundContents \- Range: surroundContents() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]Range.surroundContents()\f[B]\f[R] method moves content
of the \f[CR]Range\f[R] into a new node, placing the new node at the
start of the specified range.
.PP
This method is nearly equivalent to
\f[CR]newNode.appendChild(range.extractContents()); range.insertNode(newNode)\f[R].
After surrounding, the boundary points of the \f[CR]range\f[R] include
\f[CR]newNode\f[R].
.PP
An exception will be thrown, however, if the \f[CR]Range\f[R] splits a
non\-\f[CR]Text\f[R] node with only one of its boundary points.
That is, unlike the alternative above, if there are partially selected
nodes, they will not be cloned and instead the operation will fail.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
surroundContents(newParent)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]newParent\f[R]
A \f[CR]Node\f[R] with which to surround the contents.
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS HTML
.IP
.EX
<span class=\[dq]header\-text\[dq]>Put this in a headline</span>
.EE
.SS JavaScript
.IP
.EX
const range = document.createRange();
const newParent = document.createElement(\[dq]h1\[dq]);

range.selectNode(document.querySelector(\[dq].header\-text\[dq]));
range.surroundContents(newParent);
.EE
